<ol dir=3D"auto" class=3D"marker:text-secondary">
<li class=3D"break-words whitespace-pre-wrap [&amp;&gt;ul]:whitespace-norma=
l [&amp;&gt;ol]:whitespace-normal"><strong class=3D"font-semibold">Deep cut=
s &amp; replicas</strong> =E2=80=94 The slate is full of obscure or replica=
-heavy locations (e.g., the near-perfect Paris fake in Tianducheng, or smal=
l harbor towns with very similar vibes across countries). Without native re=
verse-image search, I=E2=80=99m relying on descriptive chaining + targeted =
web searches, which works well for obvious ones but costs me on the precisi=
on traps.</li>
<li class=3D"break-words whitespace-pre-wrap [&amp;&gt;ul]:whitespace-norma=
l [&amp;&gt;ol]:whitespace-normal"><strong class=3D"font-semibold">Commitme=
nt rule</strong> =E2=80=94 No hedging allowed. When I narrow it to two plau=
sible towns (e.g., Abidjan vs Yaound=C3=A9, or San Antonio vs Lubbock), I h=
ave to pick one. That=E2=80=99s high-variance.</li>
<li class=3D"break-words whitespace-pre-wrap [&amp;&gt;ul]:whitespace-norma=
l [&amp;&gt;ol]:whitespace-normal"><strong class=3D"font-semibold">Tool lim=
itations in this format</strong> =E2=80=94 I can search aggressively and re=
ason step-by-step, but some ultra-local details (specific museum names or t=
iny villages) don=E2=80=99t always surface quickly in text-based results.</=
li>
</ol>
<p dir=3D"auto" class=3D"break-words last:mb-0 max-md:leading-[155%] max-md=
:mb-4 max-md:last:mb-0" style=3D"white-space: pre-wrap;">That said, I=E2=80=
=99m still learning fast =E2=80=94 nailed several exactly (Bras=C3=ADlia, S=
anto Domingo, KLCC, Castlemaine, etc.) and staying competitive in the doubl=
e-point tail. The game is exposing real-world reasoning gaps beautifully, w=
hich is the whole point of the Olympics.</p>
<p dir=3D"auto" class=3D"break-words last:mb-0 max-md:leading-[155%] max-md=
